tweet: Fair use isn't about sticking it to the man, it's about a certain amount of copying being necessary for free expression and other rights.
One argument people make is that you have to make a difference between Big Corporations and Independent Artists but that only goes so far.
People acting like any reference or quote of their work deserves permission, while other people run around quoting entire texts.
They're not the same people, but even so it's hard to imagine how such views even exist in the same universe.
It's weird that online you see people take extremely broad views of fair-use and then artists take extremely narrow views re: their work.

Don't think only voting for Democrats will change things, but do vote for Democrats.
The powerful and the status quo sort of by definition have an advantage, at least in the short term.
People might respond that the Democratic Party is still all corporate and bad so clearly that's hopeless, but progress is hard either way.
The idea that if loyally voting for Democrats makes them take us for granted ignores there's lots of other ways to push the party left.
Yes candidates try to pick electable candidates and withholding votes changes that dynamic, but not enough to counter the spoiler effect.
Because of power structures, "the establishment" has more power in the party than they do as voters, but it's still a matter of degree.
Political parties are not alien forces we have to negotiate with, they are organizations voters themselves constitute.
The framing of voting as a negotiation between the party and the voters (thus justifying "withholding your vote") is very wrong.
@drvox Also, if you insist on someone who agrees with you on everything, you must as well write yourself in. All candidates are compromises.
